{
  "text": "The gravitational potential generated by the shallow layer (masses) is computed by discretized numerical integration using elementary bodies such as right-rectangular prisms and tesseroids. The integration of Eq.(1) can be completed by using prism modeling if the mass density \u03c1(K ) of each volume integral element is homogeneous. Figure 2 demonstrates the geometry of the right-rectangular prism. The prism is bounded by planes parallel to the coordinate planes, defined by the coordinates X 1 , X 2 , Y 1 , Y 2 , Z 1 , Z 2 , respectively in the Cartesian coordinate system, and the field point P is denoted by (X P , Y P , Z P ). , , , (5) will fail when P is located on a corner, an edge or a plane, as mentioned above, but one can calculate the corresponding limit values in a manner as given by [CITATION_1] Nagy et al. ( , 2002 at these special positions.",
